<pdd-reason>Async GitHub App client: auth, webhooks, issues, PRs, durable pdd-issue completion evidence, and live PR shippability gate.</pdd-reason>

<pdd-interface>
{
  "type": "module",
  "module": {
    "functions": [
      {"name": "verify_webhook_signature", "signature": "def verify_webhook_signature(payload: bytes, signature: str, secret: str) -> bool", "returns": "True if signature valid"},
      {"name": "get_installation_token", "signature": "def get_installation_token(installation_id: int) -> str", "returns": "Short-lived access token"},
      {"name": "post_issue_comment", "signature": "async def post_issue_comment(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, body: str, token: str) -> None", "returns": "None"},
      {"name": "check_user_permission", "signature": "async def check_user_permission(owner: str, repo: str, username: str, token: str) -> str", "returns": "Permission level: admin, write, read, none"},
      {"name": "get_issue_details", "signature": "async def get_issue_details(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str) -> dict", "returns": "Issue data including labels and assignees"},
      {"name": "trigger_repository_dispatch", "signature": "async def trigger_repository_dispatch(owner: str, repo: str, event_type: str, client_payload: dict, token: str) -> None", "returns": "None"},
      {"name": "create_sub_issue", "signature": "async def create_sub_issue(owner: str, repo: str, parent_issue_number: int, title: str, body: str, labels: list[str], token: str) -> dict", "returns": "{number, url, title}"},
      {"name": "list_sub_issues", "signature": "async def list_sub_issues(owner: str, repo: str, parent_issue_number: int, token: str) -> list[dict]", "returns": "List of {number, title, state, html_url}"},
      {"name": "close_issue", "signature": "async def close_issue(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "True if closed"},
      {"name": "close_pull_request", "signature": "async def close_pull_request(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "True if closed"},
      {"name": "get_pr_diff", "signature": "async def get_pr_diff(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> str", "returns": "PR diff string"},
      {"name": "GitHubAPIError", "signature": "class GitHubAPIError", "returns": ""},
      {"name": "OrgMembershipCheckError", "signature": "class OrgMembershipCheckError", "returns": ""},
      {"name": "WebhookVerificationError", "signature": "class WebhookVerificationError", "returns": ""},
      {"name": "assign_bot_to_issue", "signature": "async def assign_bot_to_issue(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str, max_retries: int=3) -> None", "returns": "None"},
      {"name": "check_org_membership", "signature": "async def check_org_membership(org: str, username: str, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "bool"},
      {"name": "create_branch", "signature": "async def create_branch(owner: str, repo: str, branch_name: str, from_ref: str, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "bool"},
      {"name": "get_issue_linked_pr_urls", "signature": "async def get_issue_linked_pr_urls(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str) -> list[str]", "returns": "List of PR URLs linked to the issue via GraphQL `Issue.closedByPullRequestsReferences` (issue→PR direction). Empty list when none, when SKIP_GITHUB_VALIDATION is set, or on unexpected response shape. Used by the pdd-checkup label handler (issue #1801)."},
      {"name": "get_pr_linked_issue_url", "signature": "async def get_pr_linked_issue_url(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> str | None", "returns": "URL of the first issue the PR closes via GraphQL `PullRequest.closingIssuesReferences` (PR→issue direction), or None when none / SKIP_GITHUB_VALIDATION / unexpected shape. Used by the pdd-checkup label handler when the label is applied to a PR (issue #1801)."},
      {"name": "find_checkup_candidate_prs", "signature": "async def find_checkup_candidate_prs(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, issue_body: str | None, token: str) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "Issue→candidate-PR detection for the pdd-checkup issue label (issue #1833), resolved in two PRECEDENCE tiers so the GitHub-native linkage from #1801 is never weakened by the broader heuristics. Lists the repo's OPEN pull requests once. Tier 1 — native close links: the OPEN PRs from `get_issue_linked_pr_urls` (`closedByPullRequestsReferences`, i.e. a `Closes #N`/`Fixes #N` keyword). When ANY open native close-linked PR exists, ONLY those are returned (a single one → checkup runs against it; several → ambiguous stop); the Tier-2 heuristics are NOT consulted, so an issue with one authoritative `Closes #N` PR still runs against it even if an unrelated open PR has an `issue-N` branch or a casual `#N` body mention. Tier 2 — heuristic discovery (fallback, ONLY when there are zero open native close links): the OPEN PRs matching ANY of — head branch named after the issue as a path segment (`issue-N`, `*/issue-N`, `fix/issue-N-cleanup`; the `(?:^|/)issue-N(?!\\d)` boundary keeps `issue-42` from matching `issue-420`); a `#N` reference in the PR body (`#N(?!\\d)`, covers `Closes #N` AND a plain cross-reference with no close keyword); a same-repo `.../pull/N` URL pasted in the issue body. Results are deduped by number and sorted ascending (as `{url, number}` dicts). Every source is reconciled against the open-PR listing so a merged/closed PR (a pasted/close-linked PR that is not open) is never returned — checkup pushes fix commits to the PR branch. Propagates GitHubAPIError/PyGithub errors (so the webhook surfaces a transient-error retry); returns [] under SKIP_GITHUB_VALIDATION."},
      {"name": "list_repo_labels", "signature": "async def list_repo_labels(owner: str, repo: str, token: str) -> list[str]", "returns": "List of label names on the repo (Issue #1690 repo health dashboard)"},
      {"name": "list_repo_action_secret_names", "signature": "async def list_repo_action_secret_names(owner: str, repo: str, token: str) -> list[str] | None", "returns": "List of GitHub Actions secret names, or None when the installation lacks the `actions:read` / `secrets:read` permission (so the UI can render an 'unknown' tri-state instead of a false ✗) — Issue #1690"},
      {"name": "list_installation_repos_detailed", "signature": "async def list_installation_repos_detailed(token: str) -> list[dict]", "returns": "List of {owner, repo, full_name} dicts for every repository the installation has access to — Issue #1690 repo health dashboard"},
      {"name": "create_or_update_file", "signature": "async def create_or_update_file(owner: str, repo: str, path: str, content: str, message: str, token: str, branch: str | None=None) -> dict[str, Any]", "returns": "dict[str, Any]"},
      {"name": "create_pull_request", "signature": "async def create_pull_request(owner: str, repo: str, title: str, head: str, base: str, body: str, token: str, draft: bool=False) -> dict[str, Any]", "returns": "dict[str, Any]"},
      {"name": "mark_pr_ready_for_review", "signature": "async def mark_pr_ready_for_review(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "True if the PR was promoted from draft to ready-for-review"},
      {"name": "create_repo_labels", "signature": "async def create_repo_labels(owner: str, repo: str, labels: list[dict[str, str]], token: str) -> list[str]", "returns": "list[str]"},
      {"name": "find_prs_for_issue", "signature": "async def find_prs_for_issue(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str, pr_state: str='open') -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "list[dict[str, Any]]"},
      {"name": "find_completion_prs_for_issue", "signature": "async def find_completion_prs_for_issue(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "All-state same-repo PR evidence for pdd-issue completion, including native close links, issue-number references, and issue-specific head branches."},
      {"name": "find_issue_completion_branches", "signature": "async def find_issue_completion_branches(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str, base_ref: str | None = None) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "Pushed same-repo issue-specific branch evidence with ref, sha, html_url, and optional base comparison metadata."},
      {"name": "get_issue_timeline_references", "signature": "async def get_issue_timeline_references(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "Current-issue timeline evidence for PRs, commits, and merges where GitHub API permissions expose it."},
      {"name": "get_commit_pull_requests", "signature": "async def get_commit_pull_requests(owner: str, repo: str, commit_sha: str, token: str) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "Pull requests associated with a commit SHA, suitable for completion-evidence correlation."},
      {"name": "get_compare_diff", "signature": "async def get_compare_diff(owner: str, repo: str, base_ref: str, head_ref: str, token: str) -> str", "returns": "str"},
      {"name": "get_file_content", "signature": "async def get_file_content(owner: str, repo: str, path: str, ref: str, token: str) -> str", "returns": "str"},
      {"name": "get_installation_repos", "signature": "async def get_installation_repos(token: str) -> list[str]", "returns": "list[str]"},
      {"name": "get_issue_comments", "signature": "async def get_issue_comments(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, token: str) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "list[dict[str, Any]]"},
      {"name": "get_pr_details", "signature": "async def get_pr_details(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> dict[str, Any]", "returns": "dict with state, merged_at, mergeable, nested head/base (head as {\"ref\", \"sha\"}), and flat head_ref/base_ref/head_sha keys. head_sha (= pr.head.sha, also at head[\"sha\"]) lets callers scope a per-commit anchor before any clone."},
      {"name": "get_pr_files", "signature": "async def get_pr_files(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> list[dict[str, Any]]", "returns": "list[dict[str, Any]]"},
      {"name": "get_repo_tree", "signature": "async def get_repo_tree(owner: str, repo: str, token: str, ref: str='HEAD', max_files: int=500) -> list[str]", "returns": "list[str]"},
      {"name": "list_prompt_files", "signature": "async def list_prompt_files(owner: str, repo: str, token: str, ref: str='HEAD') -> list[str]", "returns": "list[str]"},
      {"name": "merge_branches", "signature": "async def merge_branches(owner: str, repo: str, base: str, head: str, token: str, commit_message: str='') -> dict[str, Any]", "returns": "dict[str, Any]"},
      {"name": "remove_issue_label", "signature": "async def remove_issue_label(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, label_name: str, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "bool"},
      {"name": "validate_branch_exists", "signature": "async def validate_branch_exists(owner: str, repo: str, branch: str, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "bool"},
      {"name": "find_comment_with_anchor", "signature": "async def find_comment_with_anchor(owner: str, repo: str, issue_number: int, anchor: str, token: str) -> bool", "returns": "Iter-9 fix for PR #1460 external reviewer finding #1 (partial-crash residual). Layer 0 of the LAYERED idempotent-comment design in `solving_orchestrator.state_io.post_comment_idempotent`. Returns True when any RECENT issue comment contains the `<!-- pdd-anchor:{anchor} -->` marker; False otherwise OR on any transient API failure (fails open so the caller still posts — duplicate comments are a UX nit, strictly safer than silent comment loss). Iter-12 external reviewer P1/P2 follow-up on PR #1460 (Finding 2): the iter-10/iter-11 implementation tried `?sort=created&direction=desc` on `GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues/{issue_number}/comments`, but per GitHub's REST docs that endpoint accepts ONLY `since` / `per_page` / `page`. `sort` / `direction` are documented for the repo-wide `/issues/comments` endpoint and are silently ignored on the per-issue one. The code was therefore scanning the OLDEST 300 comments (default ascending order) — the exact opposite of intent. Iter-12 fix: use `?since=<window ago>` (`_ANCHOR_LOOKUP_SINCE_WINDOW_HOURS`) to filter by recency (`since` filters by `updated_at`, equivalent to `created_at` for never-edited anchor markers). Walk up to `_ANCHOR_LOOKUP_MAX_PAGES = 5` pages (500 comments) with early-stop on anchor match. **Iter-13 external reviewer P3 on PR #1460**: window widened from 24h to **168 hours (7 days)** because the 15-min `STALE_CLAIM_TTL` only governs CAS re-claim eligibility — it does NOT bound how long a Pub/Sub redelivery can sit before re-firing the handler. A zombie redelivery arriving >24h after the original POST would miss the anchor (outside the `since` window) and re-claim + re-POST → double comment. 7 days covers manual subscription replays, paused-subscription rehydration, dead-letter requeues, and operator-driven incident-recovery replays during weekend backlogs. Documented residual: redeliveries arriving >7 days after the original POST may re-post (UX nit, strictly preferable to silent-comment-loss). No-op (returns False) when `SKIP_GITHUB_VALIDATION` is set."},
      {"name": "get_pr_shippability_state", "signature": "async def get_pr_shippability_state(owner: str, repo: str, pr_number: int, token: str) -> dict", "returns": "dict with gate_fetchable bool, merged bool, isDraft bool, mergeable str, mergeStateStatus str, statusCheckRollup_state str|None. Fetches live PR shippability for pdd-issue completion gate (issue #2303)."}
    ]
  }
}
</pdd-interface>

<pdd-dependency>config_Python.prompt</pdd-dependency>
